            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--epi hupaton G. Kestiou M. Serouiliou Nonianou, anphipolou de en Surakousais A. Baleriou Arabikou, ton de Paidon L. Bebeiou Kladiou, hierias de Klodias Pollas, menos Panamou sk' paregenonto pors tas Paidas meta Aulias Titou thugateros Phabia Sphongeos meter kai Phabilla thugater kai Apia tei triakadi euphrandthentes kai eucharistountes Apolloni kai Paidessi kai Annai. This and the others from a cave at Buscemi, nr. Acrae; cf. the others published best also in PdP 6 (1951), and also IG XIV.204 (Acrae) for related 'hagnai theai'; P-C discusses other relevant material also. In general, note the Roman names in most of these; also the persistence of the amphipolis at Syracuse (cf. DS XVI.70.6), and the  amphipolis of the Paides, probably the eponymous amphipolis for Acrae (presumably the local city concerned). P-C observes that the 'koreion' attested in IG XIV.217 could perhaps be associated with this cult also, although P-C thinks that the Demeter-Korai and Paides cults should be kept separate in this case, although considerable overlap generally likely / common. The material in the cave doesn't go back past the C3 BC, and the whole institution is presumaly Timoleontic or later.  cf. ASNP 1981, p.1069ff for 2 oracle inscrs. from Akrai region with mentions of Nymphs and Paides.--></p>
